  "local_port": 40142,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "My H1b visa is under Admin processing for about a year now, and there's has been no update so far. What options do I have?",
  "response": "I'm not an attorney, but if your H-1B visa application has been under administrative processing for an extended period, there are several options you might consider:\n\n1. **Contact Your Employer's Immigration Attorney**: Your employer's immigration attorney can provide specific advice based on your case and may be able to expedite inquiries with the U.S. consulate or embassy handling your application.\n\n2. **Tiered Approach to Inquiry**: You or your attorney can reach out to the U.S. Department of State or the consulate handling your application for updates. Some consulates have specific phone numbers or email addresses for case statuses.\n\n3. **Request an Administrative Processing Inquiry**: After a significant amount of time, you may be able to request an inquiry to the U.S. Department of State or your lawyer can file a formal inquiry.\n\n4. **Check with Your Employer**: Keep communication open with your employer; they might have insights or updates on your case status.\n\n5. **Explore Other Visa Options**: Depending on your situation, you might have other visa options such as applying for an L-1, O-1, or even a student visa (F-1) if applicable.\n\n6. **Seek Legal Advice**: Consult with an immigration attorney for personalized advice. They can guide you through potential legal remedies available and the best course of action based on your circumstances.\n\n7. **Consider Filing a Mandamus Action**: In very specific cases, some individuals have opted to file a lawsuit to compel action on their visa application, but this is a complex process requiring legal counsel.\n\n8. **Stay Informed**: Keep yourself updated on any changes in U.S. immigration policies, especially concerning administrative processing durations and application statuses.\n\n9. **Plan for Alternatives**: If your administrative processing continues, consider developing a backup plan for your career in case the situation does not resolve favorably.\n\nMake sure to consult with an immigration attorney for the best course of action specific to your circumstances.",
